<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,150,537]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,423,258,284]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Biology and notes.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shannon &amp; Aubertin" authorityYear="1933" box="[432,792,258,284]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Chamaesphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argentifascies">
<emphasis box="[432,792,258,284]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Chamaesphegina argentifascies</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is associated with 
<taxonomicName authority="(Ruiz &amp; Pav.) Tul" authorityName="Tul" baseAuthorityName="Ruiz &amp; Pav." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Atherospermataceae" genus="Laurelia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Laurales" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sempervirens">
<emphasis box="[1014,1267,258,284]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Laurelia sempervirens</emphasis>
(Ruiz &amp; Pav.) Tul
</taxonomicName>
in the Reserva Nacional Los Queules (Rodrigo Barahona-Segovia pers. obs.) and 
<taxonomicName box="[1122,1263,294,320]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cunoniaceae" genus="Eucryphia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Oxalidales" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cordifolia">
<emphasis box="[1122,1263,294,320]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">E. cordifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
trees in Chiloé Island (Rodrigo Barahona-Segovia and C. Smith-Ramírez, pers. obs.). The locality Ensenada in the 
<typeStatus box="[1290,1338,331,357]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">type</typeStatus>
locality, belongs to the Puerto Varas municipality in Chilean territory and therefore, we considered this as an error in the geographic assignation of the 
<typeStatus box="[485,533,403,429]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">type</typeStatus>
locality. This species, especially in central 
<collectingCountry box="[1014,1075,402,428]" name="Chile" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Chile</collectingCountry>
and Valdivian forest has lost the larger extensions of native habitat by human being activities (
<bibRefCitation author="Miranda, A. &amp; Altamirano, A. &amp; Cayuela, L. &amp; Lara, A. &amp; Gonzalez, M." box="[840,1075,438,465]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="285 - 297" refId="ref134460" refString="Miranda, A., Altamirano, A., Cayuela, L., Lara, A. &amp; Gonzalez, M. (2017) Native forest loss in the Chilean biodiversity hotspot: revealing the evidence. Regional Environmental Change, 17, 285 - 297. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 10113 - 016 - 1010 - 7" type="journal article" year="2017">
Miranda 
<emphasis box="[944,1000,438,464]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">et al.</emphasis>
, 2017
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
